Friendship means nothing?<br>
<br>
Most of the people who run these guilds are people who were level 45-50 when<br>
Kunark came out, some had 2 level 50's by then! now back then there were only <br>
3 areas in all of norrath (except guards) where you could get decent exp over 45<br>
Sol B, Lower Guk and the OOT. most didnt go to the OOT because of its isolation<br>
so basicly we were all crowded into 2 zones.<br>
<br>
Suprise suprise we got to know each other! we made friends, and sometimes enemies <br>
in these zone, the first guilds were born there, died there and were reborn there.<br>
Da'Kor, Midnight Sojurne, Affliction, Storm's Fury (and on and on and on) did not just<br>
apear one day. they were all started by people who became friends and discovered they<br>
shared similar views/play styles/play times.<br>
<br>
Most of the first guilds were realy nothing more than social guilds, the Roleplay guilds<br>
were much more orginized back then, but they wern't about leveling and raiding or loot.<br>
Hell I remember most of SG warriors/shadowknights wanting to wear Blackened Iron<br>
over bronze because it looked more Evil! or Paladins in the KHS who wouldn't use a <br>
Mistmoor shield because it DID look evil!<br>
<br>
The first &quot;raid&quot; guilds were offshoots of the big social guilds that had members from 1 to 50<br>
the higher level members of the rollplay/social guild were finding more and more they were<br>
hanging out with other level 50's than participating in Rollplaying or social activites. the game<br>
had changed for them and the &quot;challange&quot; of taking down the boss mobs what what interested<br>
them the most. Sometimes this was forced, I tried rollplaying in the upper levels and was sometimes<br>
told outright to &quot;get lost&quot; that I would &quot;spoil&quot; the event because I was to high level *sigh*<br>
<br>
The level requirements are put in not to &quot;exclude&quot; anyone. they are more of a infomation<br>
thing so people who are coming up now have an idea of what level to attain before entering <br>
these guilds. If these levels were not put up in public view imagine how many /tells they would <br>
receive every day from the hoards of lower level people? <br>
<br>
Just the other day Affliction had someone who was a level 9 cleric asking to join on their <br>
EZ board. did they attack him or ridicule him for asking at such a low level? <br>
No, they explained why he would not be able to join at the present time and offered to <br>
assist him in game with any questions he had about the new game he had just bought.<br>
(he had the impression he would be able to learn his class from top players if he could<br>
just listen to guildchat).<br>
<br>
Another example is myself, I was a founding member of Affliction and for a long time I <br>
was the highest level cleric in the guild. For personal reasons (not EQ related) I quit the <br>
game and sold my account on E-Bay. About a month later the personal problems were <br>
resolved and I jumped back into the game with both feet. Initialy I joined SWM as a social <br>
guild to be in but when it disolved I found myself level 30 and guildless. My old friends in <br>
Affliction asked if I wanted back in! I refused because all I would contribute would be spam<br>
on the guildchat, but I will rejoin when I get to a level that I can assist them on raids, <br>
well assist as much as a Shadowknight can... but thats another issue. If these guilds were <br>
nothing but raids/level and loot this sort of story wouldn't happen would it?<br>
<br>
Levels over friendship? I don't think so...<br>
<br>
Naele Shadowslayer<br>
